The incidence of HIV was highest in sub- , with 1.5 new infections per 1,000 . Among adolescents and adults aged 15-49 years in sub- the incidence rate declined by 18% between 2010 and 2015 and was 2.44 men and 3.22 . Young 4 aged 15-24 years are at a particularly high risk of HIV infection, accounting for 20 % of new infections adults globally in 2015. In sub- young represented 25 % of new HIV infection adults. Overall, AIDS remains the leading cause of death aged between 15 and 49 years. Furthermore, approximately 1800 young are newly infected with HIV every day.

This study analyses the impact of economic growth and income inequality on poverty in Brazil in the from 1981 to 2013. A dynamic panel model was used, estimated by the twostep generalized method-of-moments system developed by Blundell-Bond (1998), in order to analyse three scenarios: the first corresponds to the entire period covered by this study (i.e. 1981-2013); the second encompasses the from 1981 to 1994 (the period leading up to the Real Plan); and the third is the period from 1995 to 2013 (the following the implementation of the Real Plan). The results indicate that economic growth policies that promote an increase in income in conjunction with a in income disparities are more effective in combating poverty in Brazil than those that focus only on raising mean income levels. The findings point to the existence of a pro-poor form of growth in the period following the Real Plan.

The Paris Agreement presents a historical landmark in the response to climate change and sets out the objective of limiting warming to below 2 °C and pursuing efforts to limit the temperature increase to 1.5 °C above pre-industrial . However, the climate change efforts to which Parties to the United Nations Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) have committed themselves in the form of Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) are largely insufficient, and only cover one third of the greenhouse gas emissions reductions necessary to reach this temperature goal (UNEP 2017). There is still a significant gap between 2030 emission and a -cost 2 °C pathway amounting to 11 GtCO2e or even as as 13.5 GtCO2e, taking only unconditional NDCs into account (UNEP 2017). Global greenhouse gas emissions continue to rise, albeit at a slower rate, and even though the Parties must increase the goals of their NDCs over time, it is unlikely that the emissions reductions thus achieved will be sufficient (UNEP 2017).

Climate change is already having a profound and alarming impact worldwide. Global temperatures continued to increase in 2016, setting a new record of about 1.1 degrees centigrade above the pre-industrial period. The extent of sea ice fell to 4.14 square kilometres in 2016, the second lowest on record. Atmospheric CO2 reached 400 parts per . Drought conditions predominated across of the globe, influenced by the El Niño phenomenon. In to rising sea and temperatures, extreme weather events are becoming more common and natural habitats such as coral reefs are declining. These changes affect everywhere, but disproportionately harm the poorest and the most vulnerable. Concerted action is urgently needed to stem climate change and strengthen resilience to pervasive and ever-increasing climaterelated hazards.

Finance is a term for matters regarding the management, creation, and study of money and investments.
Specifically, it deals with the questions of how and why an individual, company or government acquires the money needed - called capital in the company context - and how they spend or invest that money. Finance is then often split per the following major categories: corporate finance, personal finance and public finance.At the same time, and correspondingly, finance is about the overall "system"
 
- i.e. the financial markets that allow the flow of money, via investments and other financial instruments, between and within these areas; 
this "flow" is facilitated by the financial services sector.
A major focus within finance is thus investment management — called money management for individuals, and asset management for institutions — and finance then includes the associated activities of securities trading & stock broking, investment banking, financial engineering, and risk management. 
Given its wide scope, finance is studied in several academic disciplines, 
and, correspondingly, there are several related professional qualifications that can lead to the field.

This paper identifies the progress achieved by individual in implementing internationally recognised best policies and practices against illegal, unreported and unregulated (IUU) fishing since 2005. It aims to inspire and guide governments and all stakeholders in the fisheries sector in how to focus their effort and investment to step up their fight against IUU fishing. The paper builds on a suite of policy indicators that investigate the extent to which meet their responsibilities in the most important dimensions of government intervention in relation to IUU fishing. The indicators show considerable improvement in fighting IUU fishing over the last decade, in line with treaties and voluntary agreements. They point to the gaps that need to be closed to individually and collectively work towards eliminating IUU fishing.

Accelerating energy innovation is crucial to meet energy and goals, to support growth and to enhance energy security. Successful and deployment of innovative energy technologies requires that stakeholders from both the public and sector knowledge, work collaboratively and, where appropriate, pool resources to deliver , cost effective to common . Four decades ago, the founders of the IEA had the foresight to create a multilateral collaboration mechanism – the IEA Implementing Agreements (IAs) – that has withstood the test of time and today is more relevant than ever to delivering to global energy . This network of experts produced a range of noteworthy results, inventions, pilot plants, demonstration projects, databases and of standards. The year 2015 marked the 40th anniversary of the mechanism as well as the rebranding of the IAs as Technology Collaboration Programmes (TCPs). This publication an overview of the activities and recent accomplishments of TCPs. The 39 TCPs operating today involve about 6 000 experts from government, industry and research organisations in 51 around the world. Participants in TCPs have examined more than 1 900 energy-related topics in the areas of energy , renewable energy, fossil fuels, fusion power and cross-cutting . The unrivalled breadth and coverage of analytical expertise seen in TCPs are unique assets that will underpin for the to come IEA efforts to support innovation for energy security, growth and environmental protection.

The UNECE Real Estate Market Advisory Group (REM) is a group of real estate experts who advise the Committee on Urban Development, Housing and Land Management on real estate markets, working to identify specific measures to strengthen a country’s real estate market in a manner that would contribute to and development. In 2010, the REM Advisory Group published the “Policy Framework for Sustainable Real Estate Markets”, a tool that would help guide the member States to create real estate markets. However, the emergence of key agreements, such as the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development, the Geneva UN Charter on Sustainable Housing, the New Urban Agenda, the Paris Agreement, and the Basel III Agreement, have led to the establishment of new and regional policy frameworks for future activities on urban development at all levels. In response to the request of the Committee to update the Policy Framework to reflect the emergence of such key agreements, the REM Advisory Group produced the current publication, which now includes updates on the issues such as urbanization, migration and mobility flows, technology and innovation, the of emerging markets and asset competition, the change in housing demand oriented towards green buildings and new designs, energy consumption and climate change, and other relevant phenomena. Moreover, this version of the Policy Framework for Sustainable Real Estate Markets maintains that, contrary to the widespread belief that finance and real estate sectors have negative impact on sustainability, they can actually contribute to the achievement of Sustainable Development Goals with the of effective and compatible principles. In particular, this publication shows that these principles can be incorporated by national, local and municipal governments and applied to various forms of real estate.
